w1participation: You are invited to participate in the Spring 2025 Course Survey and Study.¬†This survey is intended to understand relationships between college students' views and attitudes about learning society and learning. You will be asked to respond to questions about the following topics:Classroom ExperienceCultural AttitudesAttitudes Toward LearningPersonal CharacteristicsBasic Demographic InformationYou will also be presented with several cognitive tasks (e.g. memory reasoning).The survey will take no more than 30 minutes to complete. You may experience some mild to moderate embarrassment when answering some questions as they may be somewhat personal in nature.¬†Participation is voluntary and your are free to withdraw from the study at any time. If you do not want to participate in this survey please email fernanr1@uci.edu to complete an alternative assignment which will involve responding to a reading which should take 30 minutes to complete.¬†This study is exempt from IRB review (UCI IRB Exempt # 13991) meaning that it does not pose any psychological or personal harm to you. As part of this study you will also complete a survey in Week 7 at which point you will be debriefed about the nature of the study and the research questions the study team is interested in answering. The survey results will be de-identified meaning that the lead researcher (Fernando Rodriguez) removes names email address and anything else that can be traced back to you prior to distributing the data.Should you have any concerns about the survey please email fernanr1@uci.edu.By completing the survey your responses may lead to important insights about college student learning and development.BestDr. Fernando Rodriguez¬†Assistant Professor of TeachingSchool of Education UC Irvine

We were with our friends acting silly but got angry when we started teasing her. She shoved me and I fell pretty bad. After that I was like¬†I‚Äôm done with you.‚ÄùWhen I asked Sandra she said ‚ÄúAmy is nice but she also has a bad side. She likes finding ways to put people down. I can‚Äôt stand how fake she can be.‚ÄùI see both girls playing in our neighborhood frequently and what is interesting about Amy and Sandra is that despite their grudge both are well adjusted. They have close friends and get along with others.While bullying is a problem in schools new research finds that having strained friendships or what‚Äôs known as¬†‚Äòfrenemies‚Äô can actually benefit children‚Äôs social development.In a recent study researchers asked 8 middle school students to privately report whether they had a friend who they actually disliked. newscontrol: üî¥?¬†Science News TodayHaving ‚ÄòFrenemies‚Äô Improves Children‚Äôs Social DevelopmentMeagan Phillips Science WriterAugust 5th 2024Social interactions among middle school students are often complex. At this age children are developing stronger relationships with peers while also learning how to navigate disagreements competition and shifting social dynamics. School environments provide opportunities not just for academic learning but also for important emotional and interpersonal development.During early adolescence many students begin to form close-knit friend groups while also encountering conflict or rivalry. These experiences can range from minor disagreements to more persistent tension.¬†Researchers are increasingly interested in how these experiences affect children‚Äôs emotional growth including their ability to manage social challenges and maintain relationships over time.While bullying is a problem in schools new research finds that having strained friendships or what‚Äôs known as¬†‚Äòfrenemies‚Äô can actually benefit children‚Äôs social development.In a recent study researchers asked 8 middle school students to privately report whether they had a friend who they actually disliked. The researchers then identified the children who disliked each other. The children with no mutual dislikes served as the comparison group.The study found that having frenemies improved children‚Äôs social development.For both girls and boys children who disliked each other scored 2 percentage points higher on a social skills assessment than children in the comparison group.While the idea is very uncomfortable to many parents it really is important to let children experience the not-so-good parts of forming friendships.Researchers suggest that learning to manage complicated peer relationships can build resilience and help children develop stronger interpersonal skills over time

newsthoughts: A ‚Äúfrenemy‚Äù-type relationship (also referred to as having a rival and friend at the same time) may actually be beneficial in terms of supporting kids' growth in important ways. For instance, having this kind of relationship motivates kids to stretch themselves but teaches them about managing conflict, cooperation, and empathy. Children then use playful competition and occasional disagreement to build up social resilience, emotional control techniques, and a greater understanding of each other's views. Instead of turning away from conflict, and learning how to manage it, is a valuable tool and skill, which we could use not only in school but also outside of school as well.
